1. The Foundation: Database Relationships
The entire system is driven by five deeply interconnected tables:
 ‚Ā†PERMISSIONS‚Ā†: The master table defining both UI and Backend rules. Critical columns include:
 ‚Ā†MENU_ACTION‚Ā†: Defines allowed UI actions (e.g., ‚Ā†view|create|modify‚Ā†).
 ‚Ā†MAPPED_REQUEST_TYPE‚Ā†: Defines the operational context (e.g., ‚Ā†CGL_CODE‚Ā†, ‚Ā†USER_MANAGEMENT‚Ā†).
 ‚Ā†API_RESOURCE_PATTERN‚Ā†: Defines the actual backend endpoints required (e.g., ‚Ā†/api/user/**‚Ā†).
 ‚Ā†ROLES‚Ā†: The master list of roles (e.g., UCO, PSO, Branch).
 ‚Ā†ROLE_PERMISSIONS‚Ā†: The bridge table mapping Roles to Permissions, including ‚Ā†PERMISSION_ORDER‚Ā† for UI sorting.
 ‚Ā†USER_ROLES‚Ā†: Maps a User to a Role.
 ‚Ā†USERS‚Ā†: The core user profiles.
Phase 1: Login & UI Rendering (Frontend Flow)
When a user attempts to log in via ‚Ā†/api/auth/login‚Ā† in the Gateway/Login Service:
1 Authentication: ‚Ā†LoginServiceImpl‚Ā† verifies the user against LDAP or the local BCrypt password.
2 Fetch Permissions: It calls ‚Ā†RolePermissionsRepository.findAllPermissionsByUserId()‚Ā†. This executes a native SQL query joining ‚Ā†USERS‚Ā† -> ‚Ā†USER_ROLES‚Ā† -> ‚Ā†ROLE_PERMISSIONS‚Ā† -> ‚Ā†PERMISSIONS‚Ā†, returning a flat list of ‚Ā†PermissionRow‚Ā† projections.
3 Transform to Hierarchy: This list is passed to ‚Ā†MenuService.transformFromProjection()‚Ā†.
 It groups items by ‚Ā†MENU_TITLE‚Ā† to create Parent/Child nested menus.
 It dynamically merges ‚Ā†MENU_ACTION‚Ā†s. For example, if a user has two submenus under "CGL Management" where one allows "create" and the other allows "approve", the root menu action becomes ‚Ā†create|approve‚Ā†.
4 Payload Delivery: The structured ‚Ā†MenuResponse‚Ā† is attached to the ‚Ā†LoginResponseDTO‚Ā†. The React frontend uses this data to dynamically render the sidebar navigation and show/hide specific action buttons based on the user's role.
Phase 2: RBAC Cache Translation (Backend Preparation)
While the frontend relies on the Login response, backend microservices do not query the database for permissions on every request. Instead, they rely on Redis.
1 Cache Warming: On startup, or when a role is modified, the ‚Ā†UserService‚Ā† triggers ‚Ā†PermissionCacheService.refreshRolePermissions(roleId)‚Ā†.
2 Translation Logic: It converts the database ‚Ā†PERMISSIONS‚Ā† rows into highly specific REST access rules.
 If ‚Ā†MENU_ACTION‚Ā† contains ‚Ā†create‚Ā† and ‚Ā†API_RESOURCE_PATTERN‚Ā† is ‚Ā†/api/user/**‚Ā†, it creates a rule: ‚Ā†POST:/api/user/**|USER_MANAGEMENT‚Ā†.
 If ‚Ā†MENU_ACTION‚Ā† contains ‚Ā†view‚Ā†, it creates a rule: ‚Ā†GET:/api/user/**|USER_MANAGEMENT‚Ā†.
3 Storage: These rules are pushed into a Redis Set under the key ‚Ā†RBAC::PERMISSIONS::{roleId}‚Ā†.
Phase 3: API Gateway Enforcement (The Gatekeeper)
When the user makes an actual API call (e.g., trying to create a user):
1 Interception: The request hits the ‚Ā†ContextRbacFilter‚Ā† (from your ‚Ā†common-utilities‚Ā† jar, deployed across services).
2 Token Extraction: The filter validates the JWT and extracts the user's ‚Ā†roleId‚Ā†.
3 Context Extraction: It reads the ‚Ā†X-Request-Type‚Ā† header (e.g., ‚Ā†USER_MANAGEMENT‚Ā†) to understand the business context of the request.
4 Redis Verification: It fetches the permissions from ‚Ā†RBAC::PERMISSIONS::{roleId}‚Ā† in Redis and uses an ‚Ā†AntPathMatcher‚Ā† to check if the incoming HTTP Method, URI, and Context match any allowed rule.
5 Decision: If a match is found, the request proceeds. If not, the filter halts the request and returns a ‚Ā†403 FORBIDDEN‚Ā† immediately, saving database and processing load.
Phase 4: Dynamic Role Creation & Real-Time Updates
Because you have a Maker-Checker flow for roles, permissions change dynamically.
1 Role Modification: When an admin uses the ‚Ā†RoleRequestController‚Ā† in ‚Ā†UserService‚Ā† to update a role's permissions, the ‚Ā†ROLE_PERMISSIONS‚Ā† database table is updated.
2 Debezium & Kafka: A Change Data Capture (CDC) tool captures this database row change and pushes an event to a Kafka topic (‚Ā†fincore.FINCORE.ROLE_PERMISSIONS‚Ā†).
3 Live Refresh: The ‚Ā†RbacEventListener‚Ā† in ‚Ā†UserService‚Ā† consumes this Kafka message in real-time, extracts the affected ‚Ā†roleId‚Ā†, and triggers ‚Ā†cacheService.refreshRolePermissions(roleId)‚Ā†.
4 Zero-Downtime: The Redis cache is instantly updated. The next time a user with that role makes an API call, ‚Ā†ContextRbacFilter‚Ā† will enforce the brand new rules‚ÄĒno application restarts required.
